Texts.Eng: A freakin' DINOSAUR EGG?!??! Wow! What can we do with it, I wonder?
A natural alcohol, Methanol can be used in a variety of ways in your lab. You'll likely want a decent amount of it. You best get it from extracting wood.
Absolutely essential in lab work involving genetics, tissue cultures open the gate to whole new areas of experimentation.
Advanced Plastic. You've opened up a whole new branch of research thanks to this helpful material. You will need quite a bit. Plant Bracken trees.
Allright...you probably shouldn't have touched this stuff. Flesh from that hideous beast. Ew. But I am positive it will be useful.
Another essential element in pesticides and fertilizers, you'll need some of this stuff if you plan to have a profitable, viable farm.
Another staple ingredient in the lab, raw minerals can be easily obtained from most types of stone via extraction. Stockpile as much as possible.
Bamboo will have little use in your lab, but it might just help you build a fancy jungle hut!
Berlinite is another extractable ore that provides direct benefits to your lab work. Place in your extractor and off you go!
Bio-spores have a great bioluminescent property that gives them some handy utility in your laboratory creations. Check it out!
Biofuel and organic research are two direct benefits to harvesting large amounts of algae. It can make all the difference in travel.
Circuitboards are somewhat essential when it comes to higher-end tech. Higher-end boards produce amazing machines.
Corvex is sort of a laboratory miracle. It does things beyond science: it can bridge impossible elements together.
Helium-3 is both a fuel and energy source. It also creates an unusual effect when in large clouds, leading to hilarity in exploration.
Hydrogen gas can be applied in a variety of ways, though you'll find it best suited in genetic research and chemistry.
I'm sure it is obvious, but you're going to need tons of DNA Samples if you intend on doing a serious amount of genetics research.
Jam this hunk of metal into your extraction lab and see what comes out. I guarantee you'll find it useful.
Methyl Iodide has but one use, and that is in the creation of pesticides. These help with hydroponics trays, producing more valuable resources.
Miscellaneous pieces of metal may seem odd to collect until you consider the tungsten they can be extracted for. Try it. You'll see!
Mutavisk silk woven into thread, ready for application in the lab. I think you'll be pleased with what it can do for you.
Nitrogen can be found in abundance all over the place if you know where to look. You'll want a fair amount of it in your research.
Putrid Slime is rare, and really quite gross. But, you'll find it has a few rather interesting uses through chemistry.
Raw, untarnished paste created from small samples of material. This is a staple in every lab, and you'll go through a ton of it.
Resin is a hard substance that has applications primarily in protective gear.
Salt is quite abundant (especially in water) and applied as a resource in numerous scientific branches.
Saltpeter is handy for explosives, and can be utilized in gene research and more besides.
Silicon has a range of uses, though for our purposes it will be used for technological devices such as microchips. Get more, you'll need it.
Silk is a high quality textile that has many useful applications.
Slimey goop may not seem useful, until you actually use some in a lab. Imagine, armor made of slime? It might come in handy...
Strictly for lab use, mineral samples none the less prove to be essential. Without them you'll be unable to produce advanced plant life.
Super tough, super malleable and utterly resistant to radiation of almost all sorts. Can you see how this is useful in clothing and armor?
Take this magnesium powder and use it to create advanced genes, or to help destabilize otherwise completely stable particles.
This barrel of pesticide is not for drinking. Trust me. Tastes awful. But you can use it in the creation and growth of amazing plants!
This sample of genetic material will prove to be an absolute necessity in your laboratory.
This strange substance is fungal in nature, with a sort of sticky property that adheres to any organic matter.
This stuff is bizarre, but can be shaped very specifically with relative ease. This means weapons, armor and equipment of a most odd sort.
This stuff is quite repulsive, actually. Blister Extract stinks like excrement before refinement, but has many exceptional uses.
This vile gas really screws up your movement ability within it, and can cause long-term damage to the psyche and immune system.
Toss this barrel of oil into an extractor to bolster your current stores of crude.
Used primarily in medical and agricultural practices. It makes for a very handy additive in some intravenous drugs, or soil enrichment from fertilizers.
Wha...I...Okay then. This is some sort of ancient technology, and it appears to interface directly into whatever touches it. It teaches ancient knowledge!
What the heck is this thing? We should probably bring it to the lab to try it out. I bet it does something gross!
Who doesn't love oxygen, am I right? Breathing is great! But oxygen has many other uses. Poke around in your lab and see.
With iodine handy graphene and methyl iodide become relatively simple to produce. I'd collect as much as you can.
With leather, you can fashion some wonderful protection from harm or the elements. You'll probably want a bit of this for a rainy day.
Without fertilizer you'll have a tougher time making and growing plants. It is especially useful in Hydroponics trays!
You'll need a fair amount of Ammonium Sulfate in your lab work. Without it you'll be unable to produce high quality fertilizers!
You've found some bone. While somewhat grisly and primitive it can still produce various useful goods including weapons and armor.
